Use ASP.NET Core's **`WebApplicationFactory<T>`** — it hosts your app in-process with a test `HttpClient`, no real port needed.

### Setup

```bash
dotnet add package Microsoft.AspNetCore.Mvc.Testing
dotnet add package xunit
```

### Example test

```csharp
public class McpIntegrationTests : IClassFixture<WebApplicationFactory<Program>>
{
    private readonly HttpClient _client;

    public McpIntegrationTests(WebApplicationFactory<Program> factory)
    {
        _client = factory.CreateClient();
    }

    [Fact]
    public async Task Initialize_ReturnsServerCapabilities()
    {
        var request = new
        {
            jsonrpc = "2.0",
            id = 1,
            method = "initialize",
            @params = new
            {
                protocolVersion = "2025-03-26",
                capabilities = new { },
                clientInfo = new { name = "test-client", version = "1.0" }
            }
        };

        var response = await _client.PostAsJsonAsync("/mcp", request);

        response.EnsureSuccessStatusCode();
        var body = await response.Content.ReadFromJsonAsync<JsonElement>();
        Assert.Equal("2.0", body.GetProperty("jsonrpc").GetString());
        Assert.Equal(1, body.GetProperty("id").GetInt32());
        Assert.True(body.GetProperty("result").TryGetProperty("capabilities", out _));
    }

    [Fact]
    public async Task ToolsList_ReturnsRegisteredTools()
    {
        var request = new { jsonrpc = "2.0", id = 2, method = "tools/list" };

        var response = await _client.PostAsJsonAsync("/mcp", request);

        response.EnsureSuccessStatusCode();
        var body = await response.Content.ReadFromJsonAsync<JsonElement>();
        var tools = body.GetProperty("result").GetProperty("tools");
        Assert.True(tools.GetArrayLength() > 0);
    }
}
```

### Key points

- **`WebApplicationFactory<Program>`** boots your real `Program` startup in-memory — middleware, DI, routing all included.
- Override services (e.g., swap a real DB for an in-memory one) via `factory.WithWebHostBuilder(b => b.ConfigureServices(...))`.
- If your MCP server uses **SSE** for streaming, use `HttpCompletionOption.ResponseHeadersRead` and read the response stream line-by-line.
- Make sure `Program` is accessible to the test project — add `InternalsVisibleTo` or a partial class declaration:

```csharp
// In your server project (e.g., bottom of Program.cs)
public partial class Program { }
```

This gives you full protocol-level coverage over real HTTP semantics with zero network overhead.
